:: the shallows [info] {"position":"2099,1000","size":"100,100"}
!The Shallows

The discovery that during storms we could walk on [[oceans]], and that the story-state could protect us from drowning in deep waters, was a boon for conch and human alike. For the conches it meant a better balance between breeding and storyholding. For the humans it meant a reduction in the number of complex rituals meant to determine who could make a tell when. Everyone understood that, without conches and the story-state they offered, drowning on land would become increasingly common. But after the discovery of the walking, and girded with speed and practice, tellers could now fan out across a broad area, the walking now making it possible for more conches to be entreated by more people.<br>

Before walking, talkers would gather for conches in the shallows, in the lakes and ponds and also in the bayous facing the mainland. Talkers sought conches in places where they could slip easily [[into and under the water->uncle]], using the sinking breath to rise into descent, and then carefully floating back to shore, story told and guided by their anchor stone. [[Emptied]].<br>

